Sydney 2000 Paralympic Games silver medallist Alex Otieno was all smiles after receiving a tri-cycle wheelchair from a well-wisher Festus Kasyoka in recognition of his physiotherapy duties at Nyayo Stadium. Otieno, 57, won silver in weight-lifting in the 2000 Paralympic Games in Australia and a bronze in the 2001 All Africa Games in Tunisia. The father of five, who was infected with polio at the age of nine, has been of great help to athletes, especially with muscle problems, and is proud to have helped sportsmen and women who have ended up becoming world beaters. Among the athletes who have benefitted from Otieno’s physiotherapy services are former Kenya professional football McDonald Maria and Dennis Oliech, 2003/2007 world women’s marathon champion, Catherine Ndereba, Former world marathon record holder and current National Olympic Committee of Kenya President Paul Tergat and 1987 world marathon champion Douglas Wakihuri.